9/// \file
10/// This file describes how to lower LLVM code to machine code. This has two
11/// main components:
12///
13/// 1. Which ValueTypes are natively supported by the target.
14/// 2. Which operations are supported for supported ValueTypes.
15/// 3. Cost thresholds for alternative implementations of certain operations.
16///
17/// In addition it has a few other components, like information about FP
18/// immediates.
19///
20//===----------------------------------------------------------------------===//

94 enum Preference {
95 None, // No preference
96 Source, // Follow source order.
97 RegPressure, // Scheduling for lowest register pressure.
98 Hybrid, // Scheduling for both latency and register pressure.
99 ILP, // Scheduling for ILP in low register pressure mode.
100 VLIW // Scheduling for VLIW targets.
101 };

105/// This base class for TargetLowering contains the SelectionDAG-independent
106/// parts that can be used from the rest of CodeGen.
107class TargetLoweringBase {
108public:
109 /// This enum indicates whether operations are valid for a target, and if not,
110 /// what action should be used to make them valid.
111 enum LegalizeAction : uint8_t {
112 Legal, // The target natively supports this operation.
113 Promote, // This operation should be executed in a larger type.
114 Expand, // Try to expand this to other ops, otherwise use a libcall.
115 LibCall, // Don't try to expand this to other ops, always use a libcall.
116 Custom // Use the LowerOperation hook to implement custom lowering.
117 };
118
119 /// This enum indicates whether a types are legal for a target, and if not,
120 /// what action should be used to make them valid.
121 enum LegalizeTypeAction : uint8_t {
122 TypeLegal, // The target natively supports this type.
123 TypePromoteInteger, // Replace this integer with a larger one.
124 TypeExpandInteger, // Split this integer into two of half the size.
125 TypeSoftenFloat, // Convert this float to a same size integer type,
126 // if an operation is not supported in target HW.
127 TypeExpandFloat, // Split this float into two of half the size.
128 TypeScalarizeVector, // Replace this one-element vector with its element.
129 TypeSplitVector, // Split this vector into two of half the size.
130 TypeWidenVector, // This vector should be widened into a larger vector.
131 TypePromoteFloat // Replace this float with a larger one.
132 };
133
134 /// LegalizeKind holds the legalization kind that needs to happen to EVT
135 /// in order to type-legalize it.
136 using LegalizeKind = std::pair<LegalizeTypeAction, EVT>;
137
138 /// Enum that describes how the target represents true/false values.
139 enum BooleanContent {
140 UndefinedBooleanContent, // Only bit 0 counts, the rest can hold garbage.
141 ZeroOrOneBooleanContent, // All bits zero except for bit 0.
142 ZeroOrNegativeOneBooleanContent // All bits equal to bit 0.
143 };
144
145 /// Enum that describes what type of support for selects the target has.
146 enum SelectSupportKind {
147 ScalarValSelect, // The target supports scalar selects (ex: cmov).
148 ScalarCondVectorVal, // The target supports selects with a scalar condition
149 // and vector values (ex: cmov).
150 VectorMaskSelect // The target supports vector selects with a vector
151 // mask (ex: x86 blends).
152 };
153
154 /// Enum that specifies what an atomic load/AtomicRMWInst is expanded
155 /// to, if at all. Exists because different targets have different levels of
156 /// support for these atomic instructions, and also have different options
157 /// w.r.t. what they should expand to.
158 enum class AtomicExpansionKind {
159 None, // Don't expand the instruction.
160 LLSC, // Expand the instruction into loadlinked/storeconditional; used
161 // by ARM/AArch64.
162 LLOnly, // Expand the (load) instruction into just a load-linked, which has
163 // greater atomic guarantees than a normal load.
164 CmpXChg, // Expand the instruction into cmpxchg; used by at least X86.
165 MaskedIntrinsic, // Use a target-specific intrinsic for the LL/SC loop.
166 };
167
168 /// Enum that specifies when a multiplication should be expanded.
169 enum class MulExpansionKind {
170 Always, // Always expand the instruction.
171 OnlyLegalOrCustom, // Only expand when the resulting instructions are legal
172 // or custom.
173 };

209 static ISD::NodeType getExtendForContent(BooleanContent Content) {
210 switch (Content) {
211 case UndefinedBooleanContent:
212 // Extend by adding rubbish bits.
213 return ISD::ANY_EXTEND;
214 case ZeroOrOneBooleanContent:
215 // Extend by adding zero bits.
216 return ISD::ZERO_EXTEND;
217 case ZeroOrNegativeOneBooleanContent:
218 // Extend by copying the sign bit.
219 return ISD::SIGN_EXTEND;
220 }
221 llvm_unreachable("Invalid content kind");
222 }

241 /// Return the pointer type for the given address space, defaults to
242 /// the pointer type from the data layout.
243 /// FIXME: The default needs to be removed once all the code is updated.
244 virtual MVT getPointerTy(const DataLayout &DL,
245 // To ease porting of backends allow defaulting to AS0
246#ifdef LLVM_TARGETLOWERINGINFO_DEFAULT_AS
247 uint32_t AS = LLVM_TARGETLOWERINGINFO_DEFAULT_AS) const {
248#else
249 uint32_t AS) const {
250#endif
251 if (DL.isFatPointer(AS))
252 return MVT::getFatPointerVT(DL.getPointerSizeInBits(AS));
253 return MVT::getIntegerVT(DL.getPointerSizeInBits(AS));
254 }

325 /// Return the preferred vector type legalization action.
326 virtual TargetLoweringBase::LegalizeTypeAction
327 getPreferredVectorAction(MVT VT) const {
328 // The default action for one element vectors is to scalarize
329 if (VT.getVectorNumElements() == 1)
330 return TypeScalarizeVector;
331 // The default action for an odd-width vector is to widen.
332 if (!VT.isPow2VectorType())
333 return TypeWidenVector;
334 // The default action for other vectors is to promote
335 return TypePromoteInteger;
336 }

338 // There are two general methods for expanding a BUILD_VECTOR node:
339 // 1. Use SCALAR_TO_VECTOR on the defined scalar values and then shuffle
340 // them together.
341 // 2. Build the vector on the stack and then load it.
342 // If this function returns true, then method (1) will be used, subject to
343 // the constraint that all of the necessary shuffles are legal (as determined
344 // by isShuffleMaskLegal). If this function returns false, then method (2) is
345 // always used. The vector type, and the number of defined values, are
346 // provided.
347 virtual bool
348 shouldExpandBuildVectorWithShuffles(EVT /* VT */,
349 unsigned DefinedValues) const {
350 return DefinedValues < 3;
351 }

424 /// Return true if the following transform is beneficial:
425 /// fold (conv (load x)) -> (load (conv*)x)
426 /// On architectures that don't natively support some vector loads
427 /// efficiently, casting the load to a smaller vector of larger types and
428 /// loading is more efficient, however, this can be undone by optimizations in
429 /// dag combiner.
430 virtual bool isLoadBitCastBeneficial(EVT LoadVT,
431 EVT BitcastVT) const {
432 // Don't do if we could do an indexed load on the original type, but not on
433 // the new one.
434 if (!LoadVT.isSimple() || !BitcastVT.isSimple())
435 return true;
436
437 MVT LoadMVT = LoadVT.getSimpleVT();
438
439 // Don't bother doing this if it's just going to be promoted again later, as
440 // doing so might interfere with other combines.
441 if (getOperationAction(ISD::LOAD, LoadMVT) == Promote &&
442 getTypeToPromoteTo(ISD::LOAD, LoadMVT) == BitcastVT.getSimpleVT())
443 return false;
444
445 return true;
446 }
447
448 /// Return true if the following transform is beneficial:
449 /// (store (y (conv x)), y*)) -> (store x, (x*))
450 virtual bool isStoreBitCastBeneficial(EVT StoreVT, EVT BitcastVT) const {
451 // Default to the same logic as loads.
452 return isLoadBitCastBeneficial(StoreVT, BitcastVT);
453 }

529 /// Return the preferred operand type if the target has a quick way to compare

538 /// Return true if the target should transform:
539 /// (X & Y) == Y ---> (~X & Y) == 0
540 /// (X & Y) != Y ---> (~X & Y) != 0
541 ///
542 /// This may be profitable if the target has a bitwise and-not operation that
543 /// sets comparison flags. A target may want to limit the transformation based
544 /// on the type of Y or if Y is a constant.
545 ///
546 /// Note that the transform will not occur if Y is known to be a power-of-2
547 /// because a mask and compare of a single bit can be handled by inverting the
548 /// predicate, for example:
549 /// (X & 8) == 8 ---> (X & 8) != 0
550 virtual bool hasAndNotCompare(SDValue Y) const {
551 return false;

558 // If the target has the more complex version of this operation, assume that
559 // it has this operation too.
560 return hasAndNotCompare(X);

631 /// For targets without i1 registers, this gives the nature of the high-bits
632 /// of boolean values held in types wider than i1.
633 ///
634 /// "Boolean values" are special true/false values produced by nodes like
635 /// SETCC and consumed (as the condition) by nodes like SELECT and BRCOND.
636 /// Not to be confused with general values promoted from i1. Some cpus
637 /// distinguish between vectors of boolean and scalars; the isVec parameter
638 /// selects between the two kinds. For example on X86 a scalar boolean should
639 /// be zero extended from i1, while the elements of a vector of booleans
640 /// should be sign extended from i1.
641 ///
642 /// Some cpus also treat floating point types the same way as they treat
643 /// vectors instead of the way they treat scalars.
644 BooleanContent getBooleanContents(bool isVec, bool isFloat) const {
645 if (isVec)
646 return BooleanVectorContents;
647 return isFloat ? BooleanFloatContents : BooleanContents;
648 }
649
650 BooleanContent getBooleanContents(EVT Type) const {
651 return getBooleanContents(Type.isVector(), Type.isFloatingPoint());
652 }

659 /// Some scheduler, e.g. hybrid, can switch to different scheduling heuristics
660 /// for different nodes. This function returns the preference (or none) for
661 /// the given node.
662 virtual Sched::Preference getSchedulingPreference(SDNode *) const {
663 return Sched::None;
664 }

666 /// Return the register class that should be used for the specified value
667 /// type.
668 virtual const TargetRegisterClass *getRegClassFor(MVT VT, bool isDivergent = false) const {
669 (void)isDivergent;
670 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = RegClassForVT[VT.SimpleTy];
671 assert(RC && "This value type is not natively supported!");

680 return false;

683 /// Return the 'representative' register class for the specified value
684 /// type.
685 ///
686 /// The 'representative' register class is the largest legal super-reg
687 /// register class for the register class of the value type. For example, on
688 /// i386 the rep register class for i8, i16, and i32 are GR32; while the rep
689 /// register class is GR64 on x86_64.

691 const TargetRegisterClass *RC = RepRegClassForVT[VT.SimpleTy];
692 return RC;

702 /// instructions, and false if a library call is preferred (e.g for code-size

708 /// Return true if the target has native support for the specified value type.
709 /// This means that it has a register that directly holds it without
710 /// promotions or expansions.
711 bool isTypeLegal(EVT VT) const {
712 assert(!VT.isSimple() ||
713 (unsigned)VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy < array_lengthof(RegClassForVT));
714 return VT.isSimple() && RegClassForVT[VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy] != nullptr;

717 class ValueTypeActionImpl {
718 /// ValueTypeActions - For each value type, keep a LegalizeTypeAction enum
719 /// that indicates how instruction selection should deal with the type.
720 LegalizeTypeAction ValueTypeActions[MVT::LAST_VALUETYPE];
721
722 public:
723 ValueTypeActionImpl() {
724 std::fill(std::begin(ValueTypeActions), std::end(ValueTypeActions),
725 TypeLegal);
726 }
727
728 LegalizeTypeAction getTypeAction(MVT VT) const {
729 return ValueTypeActions[VT.SimpleTy];
730 }
731
732 void setTypeAction(MVT VT, LegalizeTypeAction Action) {
733 ValueTypeActions[VT.SimpleTy] = Action;
734 }
735 };
736
737 const ValueTypeActionImpl &getValueTypeActions() const {
738 return ValueTypeActions;
739 }
740
741 /// Return how we should legalize values of this type, either it is already
742 /// legal (return 'Legal') or we need to promote it to a larger type (return
743 /// 'Promote'), or we need to expand it into multiple registers of smaller
744 /// integer type (return 'Expand'). 'Custom' is not an option.
745 LegalizeTypeAction getTypeAction(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
746 return getTypeConversion(Context, VT).first;
747 }
748 LegalizeTypeAction getTypeAction(MVT VT) const {
749 return ValueTypeActions.getTypeAction(VT);
750 }
751
752 /// For types supported by the target, this is an identity function. For
753 /// types that must be promoted to larger types, this returns the larger type
754 /// to promote to. For integer types that are larger than the largest integer
755 /// register, this contains one step in the expansion to get to the smaller
756 /// register. For illegal floating point types, this returns the integer type
757 /// to transform to.
758 EVT getTypeToTransformTo(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
759 return getTypeConversion(Context, VT).second;
760 }
761
762 /// For types supported by the target, this is an identity function. For
763 /// types that must be expanded (i.e. integer types that are larger than the
764 /// largest integer register or illegal floating point types), this returns
765 /// the largest legal type it will be expanded to.
766 EVT getTypeToExpandTo(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
767 assert(!VT.isVector());
768 while (true) {
769 switch (getTypeAction(Context, VT)) {
770 case TypeLegal:
771 return VT;
772 case TypeExpandInteger:
773 VT = getTypeToTransformTo(Context, VT);
774 break;
775 default:
776 llvm_unreachable("Type is not legal nor is it to be expanded!");
777 }
778 }
779 }

781 /// Vector types are broken down into some number of legal first class types.
782 /// For example, EVT::v8f32 maps to 2 EVT::v4f32 with Altivec or SSE1, or 8
783 /// promoted EVT::f64 values with the X86 FP stack. Similarly, EVT::v2i64
784 /// turns into 4 EVT::i32 values with both PPC and X86.
785 ///
786 /// This method returns the number of registers needed, and the VT for each
787 /// register. It also returns the VT and quantity of the intermediate values
788 /// before they are promoted/expanded.
789 unsigned getVectorTypeBreakdown(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT,
790 EVT &IntermediateVT,
791 unsigned &NumIntermediates,
792 MVT &RegisterVT) const;
793
794 /// Certain targets such as MIPS require that some types such as vectors are
795 /// always broken down into scalars in some contexts. This occurs even if the
796 /// vector type is legal.
797 virtual unsigned getVectorTypeBreakdownForCallingConv(
798 LLVMContext &Context, CallingConv::ID CC, EVT VT, EVT &IntermediateVT,
799 unsigned &NumIntermediates, MVT &RegisterVT) const {
800 return getVectorTypeBreakdown(Context, VT, IntermediateVT, NumIntermediates,
801 RegisterVT);
802 }

860 /// Return how this operation should be treated: either it is legal, needs to
861 /// be promoted to a larger size, needs to be expanded to some other code
862 /// sequence, or the target has a custom expander for it.
863 LegalizeAction getOperationAction(unsigned Op, EVT VT) const {
864 if (VT.isExtended()) return Expand;
865 // If a target-specific SDNode requires legalization, require the target
866 // to provide custom legalization for it.
867 if (Op >= array_lengthof(OpActions[0])) return Custom;
868 return OpActions[(unsigned)VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy][Op];
869 }

871 /// Custom method defined by each target to indicate if an operation which
872 /// may require a scale is supported natively by the target.
873 /// If not, the operation is illegal.
874 virtual bool isSupportedFixedPointOperation(unsigned Op, EVT VT,
875 unsigned Scale) const {
876 return false;
877 }
878
879 /// Some fixed point operations may be natively supported by the target but
880 /// only for specific scales. This method allows for checking
881 /// if the width is supported by the target for a given operation that may
882 /// depend on scale.
883 LegalizeAction getFixedPointOperationAction(unsigned Op, EVT VT,
884 unsigned Scale) const {
885 auto Action = getOperationAction(Op, VT);
886 if (Action != Legal)
887 return Action;
888
889 // This operation is supported in this type but may only work on specific
890 // scales.
891 bool Supported;
892 switch (Op) {
893 default:
894 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected fixed point operation.");
895 case ISD::SMULFIX:
896 case ISD::SMULFIXSAT:
897 case ISD::UMULFIX:
898 Supported = isSupportedFixedPointOperation(Op, VT, Scale);
899 break;
900 }
901
902 return Supported ? Action : Expand;
903 }
904
905 LegalizeAction getStrictFPOperationAction(unsigned Op, EVT VT) const {
906 unsigned EqOpc;
907 switch (Op) {
908 default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected FP pseudo-opcode");
909 case ISD::STRICT_FADD: EqOpc = ISD::FADD; break;
910 case ISD::STRICT_FSUB: EqOpc = ISD::FSUB; break;
911 case ISD::STRICT_FMUL: EqOpc = ISD::FMUL; break;
912 case ISD::STRICT_FDIV: EqOpc = ISD::FDIV; break;
913 case ISD::STRICT_FREM: EqOpc = ISD::FREM; break;
914 case ISD::STRICT_FSQRT: EqOpc = ISD::FSQRT; break;
915 case ISD::STRICT_FPOW: EqOpc = ISD::FPOW; break;
916 case ISD::STRICT_FPOWI: EqOpc = ISD::FPOWI; break;
917 case ISD::STRICT_FMA: EqOpc = ISD::FMA; break;
918 case ISD::STRICT_FSIN: EqOpc = ISD::FSIN; break;
919 case ISD::STRICT_FCOS: EqOpc = ISD::FCOS; break;
920 case ISD::STRICT_FEXP: EqOpc = ISD::FEXP; break;
921 case ISD::STRICT_FEXP2: EqOpc = ISD::FEXP2; break;
922 case ISD::STRICT_FLOG: EqOpc = ISD::FLOG; break;
923 case ISD::STRICT_FLOG10: EqOpc = ISD::FLOG10; break;
924 case ISD::STRICT_FLOG2: EqOpc = ISD::FLOG2; break;
925 case ISD::STRICT_FRINT: EqOpc = ISD::FRINT; break;
926 case ISD::STRICT_FNEARBYINT: EqOpc = ISD::FNEARBYINT; break;
927 case ISD::STRICT_FMAXNUM: EqOpc = ISD::FMAXNUM; break;
928 case ISD::STRICT_FMINNUM: EqOpc = ISD::FMINNUM; break;
929 case ISD::STRICT_FCEIL: EqOpc = ISD::FCEIL; break;
930 case ISD::STRICT_FFLOOR: EqOpc = ISD::FFLOOR; break;
931 case ISD::STRICT_FROUND: EqOpc = ISD::FROUND; break;
932 case ISD::STRICT_FTRUNC: EqOpc = ISD::FTRUNC; break;
933 case ISD::STRICT_FP_ROUND: EqOpc = ISD::FP_ROUND; break;
934 case ISD::STRICT_FP_EXTEND: EqOpc = ISD::FP_EXTEND; break;
935 }
936
937 auto Action = getOperationAction(EqOpc, VT);
938
939 // We don't currently handle Custom or Promote for strict FP pseudo-ops.
940 // For now, we just expand for those cases.
941 if (Action != Legal)
942 Action = Expand;
943
944 return Action;
945 }

990 /// Check whether the range [Low,High] fits in a machine word.
991 bool rangeFitsInWord(const APInt &Low, const APInt &High,
992 const DataLayout &DL) const {
993 // FIXME: Using the pointer type doesn't seem ideal.
994 // XXXAR: AS0 hardcoded
995 uint64_t BW = DL.getIndexSizeInBits(0u);
996 uint64_t Range = (High - Low).getLimitedValue(UINT64_MAX - 1) + 1;
997 return Range <= BW;
998 }
999
1000 /// Return true if lowering to a jump table is suitable for a set of case
1001 /// clusters which may contain \p NumCases cases, \p Range range of values.
1002 /// FIXME: This function check the maximum table size and density, but the
1003 /// minimum size is not checked. It would be nice if the minimum size is
1004 /// also combined within this function. Currently, the minimum size check is
1005 /// performed in findJumpTable() in SelectionDAGBuiler and
1006 /// getEstimatedNumberOfCaseClusters() in BasicTTIImpl.
1007 virtual bool isSuitableForJumpTable(const SwitchInst *SI, uint64_t NumCases,
1008 uint64_t Range) const {
1009 const bool OptForSize = SI->getParent()->getParent()->hasOptSize();
1010 const unsigned MinDensity = getMinimumJumpTableDensity(OptForSize);
1011 const unsigned MaxJumpTableSize =
1012 OptForSize ? UINT_MAX : getMaximumJumpTableSize();
1013 // Check whether a range of clusters is dense enough for a jump table.
1014 if (Range <= MaxJumpTableSize &&
1015 (NumCases * 100 >= Range * MinDensity)) {
1016 return true;
1017 }
1018 return false;
1019 }
1020
1021 /// Return true if lowering to a bit test is suitable for a set of case
1022 /// clusters which contains \p NumDests unique destinations, \p Low and
1023 /// \p High as its lowest and highest case values, and expects \p NumCmps
1024 /// case value comparisons. Check if the number of destinations, comparison
1025 /// metric, and range are all suitable.
1026 bool isSuitableForBitTests(unsigned NumDests, unsigned NumCmps,
1027 const APInt &Low, const APInt &High,
1028 const DataLayout &DL) const {
1029 // FIXME: I don't think NumCmps is the correct metric: a single case and a
1030 // range of cases both require only one branch to lower. Just looking at the
1031 // number of clusters and destinations should be enough to decide whether to
1032 // build bit tests.
1033
1034 // To lower a range with bit tests, the range must fit the bitwidth of a
1035 // machine word.
1036 if (!rangeFitsInWord(Low, High, DL))
1037 return false;
1038
1039 // Decide whether it's profitable to lower this range with bit tests. Each
1040 // destination requires a bit test and branch, and there is an overall range
1041 // check branch. For a small number of clusters, separate comparisons might
1042 // be cheaper, and for many destinations, splitting the range might be
1043 // better.
1044 return (NumDests == 1 && NumCmps >= 3) || (NumDests == 2 && NumCmps >= 5) ||
1045 (NumDests == 3 && NumCmps >= 6);
1046 }

1061 /// Return how this load with extension should be treated: either it is legal,
1062 /// needs to be promoted to a larger size, needs to be expanded to some other
1063 /// code sequence, or the target has a custom expander for it.
1064 LegalizeAction getLoadExtAction(unsigned ExtType, EVT ValVT,
1065 EVT MemVT) const {
1066 if (ValVT.isExtended() || MemVT.isExtended()) return Expand;
1067 unsigned ValI = (unsigned) ValVT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy;

1070 MemI < MVT::LAST_VALUETYPE && "Table isn't big enough!");

1073 }

1149 /// Return how the condition code should be treated: either it is legal, needs
1150 /// to be expanded to some other code sequence, or the target has a custom
1151 /// expander for it.
1152 LegalizeAction
1153 getCondCodeAction(ISD::CondCode CC, MVT VT) const {
1154 assert((unsigned)CC < array_lengthof(CondCodeActions) &&
1155 ((unsigned)VT.SimpleTy >> 3) < array_lengthof(CondCodeActions[0]) &&
1156 "Table isn't big enough!");
1157 // See setCondCodeAction for how this is encoded.
1158 uint32_t Shift = 4 * (VT.SimpleTy & 0x7);
1159 uint32_t Value = CondCodeActions[CC][VT.SimpleTy >> 3];
1160 LegalizeAction Action = (LegalizeAction) ((Value >> Shift) & 0xF);
1161 assert(Action != Promote && "Can't promote condition code!");
1162 return Action;
1163 }

1174 getCondCodeAction(CC, VT) == Custom;

1177 /// If the action for this operation is to promote, this method returns the
1178 /// ValueType to promote to.
1179 MVT getTypeToPromoteTo(unsigned Op, MVT VT) const {
1180 assert(getOperationAction(Op, VT) == Promote &&
1181 "This operation isn't promoted!");
1182
1183 // See if this has an explicit type specified.
1184 std::map<std::pair<unsigned, MVT::SimpleValueType>,
1185 MVT::SimpleValueType>::const_iterator PTTI =
1186 PromoteToType.find(std::make_pair(Op, VT.SimpleTy));
1187 if (PTTI != PromoteToType.end()) return PTTI->second;
1188
1189 assert((VT.isInteger() || VT.isFloatingPoint()) &&
1190 "Cannot autopromote this type, add it with AddPromotedToType.");
1191
1192 MVT NVT = VT;
1193 do {
1194 NVT = (MVT::SimpleValueType)(NVT.SimpleTy+1);
1195 assert(NVT.isInteger() == VT.isInteger() && NVT != MVT::isVoid &&
1196 "Didn't find type to promote to!");
1197 } while (!isTypeLegal(NVT) ||
1198 getOperationAction(Op, NVT) == Promote);
1199 return NVT;
1200 }
1201
1202 /// Return the EVT corresponding to this LLVM type. This is fixed by the LLVM
1203 /// operations except for the pointer size. If AllowUnknown is true, this
1204 /// will return MVT::Other for types with no EVT counterpart (e.g. structs),
1205 /// otherwise it will assert.
1206 EVT getValueType(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty,
1207 bool AllowUnknown = false) const {
1208 // Lower scalar pointers to native pointer types.
1209 if (auto *PTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(Ty))
1210 return getPointerTy(DL, Ty->getPointerAddressSpace());
1211
1212 if (auto *VTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Ty)) {
1213 Type *EltTy = VTy->getElementType();
1214 // Lower vectors of pointers to native pointer types.
1215 if (auto *PTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(EltTy)) {
1216 EVT PointerTy(getPointerTy(DL, PTy->getAddressSpace()));
1217 EltTy = PointerTy.getTypeForEVT(Ty->getContext());
1218 }
1219 return EVT::getVectorVT(Ty->getContext(), EVT::getEVT(EltTy, false),
1220 VTy->getNumElements());
1221 }
1222
1223 return EVT::getEVT(Ty, AllowUnknown);
1224 }
1225
1226 EVT getMemValueType(const DataLayout &DL, Type *Ty,
1227 bool AllowUnknown = false) const {
1228 // Lower scalar pointers to native pointer types.
1229 if (PointerType *PTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(Ty))
1230 return getPointerMemTy(DL, PTy->getAddressSpace());
1231 else if (VectorType *VTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(Ty)) {
1232 Type *Elm = VTy->getElementType();
1233 if (PointerType *PT = dyn_cast<PointerType>(Elm)) {
1234 EVT PointerTy(getPointerMemTy(DL, PT->getAddressSpace()));
1235 Elm = PointerTy.getTypeForEVT(Ty->getContext());
1236 }
1237 return EVT::getVectorVT(Ty->getContext(), EVT::getEVT(Elm, false),
1238 VTy->getNumElements());
1239 }
1240
1241 return getValueType(DL, Ty, AllowUnknown);
1242 }

1262 /// Return the type of registers that this ValueType will eventually require.
1263 MVT getRegisterType(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
1264 if (VT.isSimple()) {
1265 assert((unsigned)VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy <
1266 array_lengthof(RegisterTypeForVT));
1267 return RegisterTypeForVT[VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy];
1268 }
1269 if (VT.isVector()) {
1270 EVT VT1;
1271 MVT RegisterVT;
1272 unsigned NumIntermediates;
1273 (void)getVectorTypeBreakdown(Context, VT, VT1,
1274 NumIntermediates, RegisterVT);
1275 return RegisterVT;
1276 }
1277 if (VT.isInteger()) {
1278 return getRegisterType(Context, getTypeToTransformTo(Context, VT));
1279 }
1280 llvm_unreachable("Unsupported extended type!");
1281 }
1282
1283 /// Return the number of registers that this ValueType will eventually
1284 /// require.
1285 ///
1286 /// This is one for any types promoted to live in larger registers, but may be
1287 /// more than one for types (like i64) that are split into pieces. For types
1288 /// like i140, which are first promoted then expanded, it is the number of
1289 /// registers needed to hold all the bits of the original type. For an i140
1290 /// on a 32 bit machine this means 5 registers.
1291 unsigned getNumRegisters(LLVMContext &Context, EVT VT) const {
1292 if (VT.isSimple()) {
1293 assert((unsigned)VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy <
1294 array_lengthof(NumRegistersForVT));
1295 return NumRegistersForVT[VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy];
1296 }
1297 if (VT.isVector()) {
1298 EVT VT1;
1299 MVT VT2;
1300 unsigned NumIntermediates;
1301 return getVectorTypeBreakdown(Context, VT, VT1, NumIntermediates, VT2);
1302 }
1303 if (VT.isInteger()) {
1304 unsigned BitWidth = VT.getSizeInBits();
1305 unsigned RegWidth = getRegisterType(Context, VT).getSizeInBits();
1306 return (BitWidth + RegWidth - 1) / RegWidth;
1307 }
1308 llvm_unreachable("Unsupported extended type!");
1309 }

1729 /// Inserts in the IR a target-specific intrinsic specifying a fence.
1730 /// It is called by AtomicExpandPass before expanding an
1731 /// AtomicRMW/AtomicCmpXchg/AtomicStore/AtomicLoad
1732 /// if shouldInsertFencesForAtomic returns true.
1733 ///
1734 /// Inst is the original atomic instruction, prior to other expansions that
1735 /// may be performed.
1736 ///
1737 /// This function should either return a nullptr, or a pointer to an IR-level
1738 /// Instruction*. Even complex fence sequences can be represented by a
1739 /// single Instruction* through an intrinsic to be lowered later.
1740 /// Backends should override this method to produce target-specific intrinsic
1741 /// for their fences.
1742 /// FIXME: Please note that the default implementation here in terms of
1743 /// IR-level fences exists for historical/compatibility reasons and is
1744 /// *unsound* ! Fences cannot, in general, be used to restore sequential
1745 /// consistency. For example, consider the following example:
1746 /// atomic<int> x = y = 0;
1747 /// int r1, r2, r3, r4;
1748 /// Thread 0:
1749 /// x.store(1);
1750 /// Thread 1:
1751 /// y.store(1);
1752 /// Thread 2:
1753 /// r1 = x.load();
1754 /// r2 = y.load();
1755 /// Thread 3:
1756 /// r3 = y.load();
1757 /// r4 = x.load();
1758 /// r1 = r3 = 1 and r2 = r4 = 0 is impossible as long as the accesses are all
1759 /// seq_cst. But if they are lowered to monotonic accesses, no amount of
1760 /// IR-level fences can prevent it.
1761 /// @{
1762 virtual Instruction *emitLeadingFence(IRBuilder<> &Builder, Instruction *Inst,
1763 AtomicOrdering Ord) const {
1764 if (isReleaseOrStronger(Ord) && Inst->hasAtomicStore())
1765 return Builder.CreateFence(Ord);
1766 else
1767 return nullptr;
1768 }
1769
1770 virtual Instruction *emitTrailingFence(IRBuilder<> &Builder,
1771 Instruction *Inst,
1772 AtomicOrdering Ord) const {
1773 if (isAcquireOrStronger(Ord))
1774 return Builder.CreateFence(Ord);
1775 else
1776 return nullptr;
1777 }

1826 /// On some platforms, an AtomicRMW that never actually modifies the value
1827 /// (such as fetch_add of 0) can be turned into a fence followed by an
1828 /// atomic load. This may sound useless, but it makes it possible for the
1829 /// processor to keep the cacheline shared, dramatically improving
1830 /// performance. And such idempotent RMWs are useful for implementing some
1831 /// kinds of locks, see for example (justification + benchmarks):

1836 /// another round of expansion.

1839 return nullptr;

1850 /// Returns true if we should normalize
1851 /// select(N0&N1, X, Y) => select(N0, select(N1, X, Y), Y) and
1852 /// select(N0|N1, X, Y) => select(N0, select(N1, X, Y, Y)) if it is likely
1853 /// that it saves us from materializing N0 and N1 in an integer register.
1854 /// Targets that are able to perform and/or on flags should return false here.
1855 virtual bool shouldNormalizeToSelectSequence(LLVMContext &Context,
1856 EVT VT) const {
1857 // If a target has multiple condition registers, then it likely has logical
1858 // operations on those registers.
1859 if (hasMultipleConditionRegisters())
1860 return false;
1861 // Only do the transform if the value won't be split into multiple
1862 // registers.
1863 LegalizeTypeAction Action = getTypeAction(Context, VT);
1864 return Action != TypeExpandInteger && Action != TypeExpandFloat &&
1865 Action != TypeSplitVector;
1866 }

2004 /// Indicate that the specified load with extension does not work with the
2005 /// specified type and indicate what to do about it.
2006 void setLoadExtAction(unsigned ExtType, MVT ValVT, MVT MemVT,
2007 LegalizeAction Action) {
2008 assert(ExtType < ISD::LAST_LOADEXT_TYPE && ValVT.isValid() &&
2009 MemVT.isValid() && "Table isn't big enough!");
2010 assert((unsigned)Action < 0x10 && "too many bits for bitfield array");

2024 /// Indicate that the specified indexed load does or does not work with the
2025 /// specified type and indicate what to do abort it.
2026 ///
2027 /// NOTE: All indexed mode loads are initialized to Expand in
2028 /// TargetLowering.cpp
2029 void setIndexedLoadAction(unsigned IdxMode, MVT VT,
2030 LegalizeAction Action) {
2031 assert(VT.isValid() && IdxMode < ISD::LAST_INDEXED_MODE &&
2032 (unsigned)Action < 0xf && "Table isn't big enough!");
2033 // Load action are kept in the upper half.
2034 IndexedModeActions[(unsigned)VT.SimpleTy][IdxMode] &= ~0xf0;
2035 IndexedModeActions[(unsigned)VT.SimpleTy][IdxMode] |= ((uint8_t)Action) <<4;

2041 /// NOTE: All indexed mode stores are initialized to Expand in

2043 void setIndexedStoreAction(unsigned IdxMode, MVT VT,
2044 LegalizeAction Action) {
2045 assert(VT.isValid() && IdxMode < ISD::LAST_INDEXED_MODE &&
2046 (unsigned)Action < 0xf && "Table isn't big enough!");
2047 // Store action are kept in the lower half.

2052 /// Indicate that the specified condition code is or isn't supported on the
2053 /// target and indicate what to do about it.
2054 void setCondCodeAction(ISD::CondCode CC, MVT VT,
2055 LegalizeAction Action) {
2056 assert(VT.isValid() && (unsigned)CC < array_lengthof(CondCodeActions) &&
2057 "Table isn't big enough!");
2058 assert((unsigned)Action < 0x10 && "too many bits for bitfield array");
2059 /// The lower 3 bits of the SimpleTy index into Nth 4bit set from the 32-bit
2060 /// value and the upper 29 bits index into the second dimension of the array
2061 /// to select what 32-bit value to use.
2062 uint32_t Shift = 4 * (VT.SimpleTy & 0x7);
2063 CondCodeActions[CC][VT.SimpleTy >> 3] &= ~((uint32_t)0xF << Shift);
2064 CondCodeActions[CC][VT.SimpleTy >> 3] |= (uint32_t)Action << Shift;
2065 }

2160 /// This represents an addressing mode of:
2161 /// BaseGV + BaseOffs + BaseReg + Scale*ScaleReg
2162 /// If BaseGV is null, there is no BaseGV.
2163 /// If BaseOffs is zero, there is no base offset.

2166 /// no scale.

2169 int64_t BaseOffs = 0;
2170 bool HasBaseReg = false;
2171 int64_t Scale = 0;
2172 AddrMode() = default;

2317 /// Return true if the extension represented by \p I is free.
2318 /// Unlikely the is[Z|FP]ExtFree family which is based on types,
2319 /// this method can use the context provided by \p I to decide
2320 /// whether or not \p I is free.
2321 /// This method extends the behavior of the is[Z|FP]ExtFree family.
2322 /// In other words, if is[Z|FP]Free returns true, then this method
2323 /// returns true as well. The converse is not true.
2324 /// The target can perform the adequate checks by overriding isExtFreeImpl.
2325 /// \pre \p I must be a sign, zero, or fp extension.
2326 bool isExtFree(const Instruction *I) const {
2327 switch (I->getOpcode()) {
2328 case Instruction::FPExt:
2329 if (isFPExtFree(EVT::getEVT(I->getType()),
2330 EVT::getEVT(I->getOperand(0)->getType())))
2331 return true;
2332 break;
2333 case Instruction::ZExt:
2334 if (isZExtFree(I->getOperand(0)->getType(), I->getType()))
2335 return true;
2336 break;
2337 case Instruction::SExt:
2338 break;
2339 default:
2340 llvm_unreachable("Instruction is not an extension");
2341 }
2342 return isExtFreeImpl(I);
2343 }

2345 /// Return true if \p Load and \p Ext can form an ExtLoad.
2346 /// For example, in AArch64
2347 /// %L = load i8, i8* %ptr
2348 /// %E = zext i8 %L to i32
2349 /// can be lowered into one load instruction
2350 /// ldrb w0, [x0]
2351 bool isExtLoad(const LoadInst *Load, const Instruction *Ext,
2352 const DataLayout &DL) const {
2353 EVT VT = getValueType(DL, Ext->getType());
2354 EVT LoadVT = getValueType(DL, Load->getType());
2355
2356 // If the load has other users and the truncate is not free, the ext
2357 // probably isn't free.
2358 if (!Load->hasOneUse() && (isTypeLegal(LoadVT) || !isTypeLegal(VT)) &&
2359 !isTruncateFree(Ext->getType(), Load->getType()))
2360 return false;
2361
2362 // Check whether the target supports casts folded into loads.
2363 unsigned LType;
2364 if (isa<ZExtInst>(Ext))
2365 LType = ISD::ZEXTLOAD;
2366 else {
2367 assert(isa<SExtInst>(Ext) && "Unexpected ext type!");
2368 LType = ISD::SEXTLOAD;
2369 }
2370
2371 return isLoadExtLegal(LType, VT, LoadVT);
2372 }

3086 /// Look at Op. At this point, we know that only the DemandedBits bits of the
3087 /// result of Op are ever used downstream. If we can use this information to
3088 /// simplify Op, create a new simplified DAG node and return true, returning
3089 /// the original and new nodes in Old and New. Otherwise, analyze the
3090 /// expression and return a mask of KnownOne and KnownZero bits for the
3091 /// expression (used to simplify the caller). The KnownZero/One bits may only
3092 /// be accurate for those bits in the Demanded masks.
3093 /// \p AssumeSingleUse When this parameter is true, this function will
3094 /// attempt to simplify \p Op even if there are multiple uses.
3095 /// Callers are responsible for correctly updating the DAG based on the
3096 /// results of this function, because simply replacing replacing TLO.Old
3097 /// with TLO.New will be incorrect when this parameter is true and TLO.Old
3098 /// has multiple uses.

3101 TargetLoweringOpt &TLO, unsigned Depth = 0,
3102 bool AssumeSingleUse = false) const;

3712 enum ConstraintType {
3713 C_Register, // Constraint represents specific register(s).
3714 C_RegisterClass, // Constraint represents any of register(s) in class.
3715 C_Memory, // Memory constraint.
3716 C_Other, // Something else.
3717 C_Unknown // Unsupported constraint.

3720 enum ConstraintWeight {
3721 // Generic weights.
3722 CW_Invalid = -1, // No match.
3723 CW_Okay = 0, // Acceptable.
3724 CW_Good = 1, // Good weight.
3725 CW_Better = 2, // Better weight.
3726 CW_Best = 3, // Best weight.
3727
3728 // Well-known weights.
3729 CW_SpecificReg = CW_Okay, // Specific register operands.
3730 CW_Register = CW_Good, // Register operands.
3731 CW_Memory = CW_Better, // Memory operands.
3732 CW_Constant = CW_Best, // Constant operand.
3733 CW_Default = CW_Okay // Default or don't know type.
3734 };
